  "entries": [
    {
      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Implement mandatory Google warmup phase before target crawl using camoufox-js\n**Description**: Add a warmup step in src/main.ts that launches a standalone Camoufox browser page (via src/warmup.ts), visits google.com, performs human-like interactions (typing, mouse moves, cookie dismissal) to warm the fingerprint, then closes the page before the actual crawling begins. Reuses existing proxy and launch options. No new dependencies needed.\n## All Steps\n1. **Create warmup function in src/warmup.ts**: ## Goal\n\nCreate a new module `src/warmup.ts` that exports an async function `warmupBrowser()`. This function launches a standalone Camoufox browser page, navigates to https://www.google.com, performs human-like interactions (typing, mouse movement, cookie dismissal), waits a short time, then closes the page and browser. The warmup must run **before** the actual crawling begins, ensuring the Camoufox fingerprint is “warm” and the proxy session is established, reducing detection risk.\n\n## Task Type\n\n**New file creation** – Write a self-contained async function that reuses existing Camoufox launch options and proxy configuration from `src/main.ts`. The function will be called from `main.ts` later, but in this step only the module is created.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n\n- **Entry point**: `src/main.ts` – reads input, creates `proxyConfiguration` (RESIDENTIAL, IT), instantiates `PlaywrightCrawler` with Camoufox `launchOptions`.\n- **Launch options** (lines ~148–160 of `main.ts`):\n  - `headless: true` (or controlled by input)\n  - `window: { width: 1280, height: 720 }`\n  - `proxy: proxyUrl` from proxyConfiguration\n  - `geoip: true`\n  - `locale: 'it-IT'`\n  - `humanize: true`\n  - `verbose: true` (sometimes)\n  - `blockAds: true`\n- These options are used when creating the crawler via `new PlaywrightCrawler({ launchContext: { launchOptions }, ... })`.\n- The warmup must use **the same Camoufox browser launch options** to maintain fingerprint consistency. The crawler’s `launchOptions` object is accessible; the warmup will need to accept it as a parameter.\n- No new npm dependencies are needed. The project already has `camoufox-js`, `playwright`, and `@crawlee/playwright`.\n- All browser automation must happen via Playwright API (Camoufox is a Playwright fork). Use `firefox.launch()` from `playwright` or the Camoufox equivalent. The project’s `launchOptions` includes `channel: ''` or similar; use `firefox.launch(launchOptions)`.\n- **Proxy**: The `proxyUrl` is passed in `launchOptions`. The warmup must accept an optional `proxyUrl` parameter (string) and include it in the launch options if provided.\n- Google interactions: navigate to `https://www.google.com`, wait for load, click the search box, type a random benign query (e.g., “Apify web scraping”), simulate typing delay, move mouse randomly, wait for results, dismiss cookie banner if present (`button:has-text('Accetta tutto')` or `button:has-text('Accept all')`), wait 2–3 seconds, then close the page and browser.\n- Use `apify/log` for logging (prefix with `[Warmup]`).\n\n## Action\n\n1. Create file `src/warmup.ts`.\n2. Export an async function with signature:\n   ```typescript\n   export async function warmupBrowser(launchOptions: any, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>\n   ```\n   - `launchOptions` is the Camoufox browser launch options object (as used in main.ts).\n   - `proxyUrl` is optional; if provided, it overrides or sets `launchOptions.proxy`.\n3. Inside `warmupBrowser`:\n   - Import `firefox` from `playwright` (or `camoufox-js` – verify which is correct; the project uses `@crawlee/playwright` which internally uses camoufox, but direct launch should use `playwright`). Use `import { firefox } from 'playwright';`.\n   - Merge `proxyUrl` into `launchOptions` if provided.\n   - Log `'[Warmup] Launching browser for warmup…'`.\n   - Launch browser: `const browser = await firefox.launch(launchOptions);`\n   - Create a new context: `const context = await browser.newContext({ viewport: { width: 1280, height: 720 } });`\n   - Create a page: `const page = await context.newPage();`\n   - Log `'[Warmup] Navigating to https://www.google.com'`.\n   - Go to Google: `await page.goto('https://www.google.com', { waitUntil: 'networkidle' });`\n   - Accept cookie consent if present (using Italian locale it might be Italian text – handle both Italian and English).\n   - Wait for search box selector: `input[name=\"q\"]`.\n   - Click on search box, type a query with realistic delays (`page.keyboard.type('Apify web scraping', { delay: 100 })`).\n   - Simulate mouse moves: `await page.mouse.move(100, 200); await page.wait(500);`\n   - Wait for results: `await page.waitForSelector('#search', { timeout: 5000 }).catch(() => {});`\n   - Wait an additional 2 seconds.\n   - Log `'[Warmup] Warmup complete, closing page…'`.\n   - Close page: `await page.close();`\n   - Close browser: `await browser.close();`\n4. Use `try/catch/finally` to ensure browser is always closed even on error.\n5. Log any errors at `warn` level but do not throw – warmup failure should not block the crawl. Log `'[Warmup] Failed but continuing: …'`.\n\n## Reasoning\n\n- Warmup is **mandatory** (not configurable) to improve stealth. By visiting a trusted site like Google with realistic interactions, the Camoufox fingerprint becomes stable and the proxy IP session is active before hitting target sites.\n- Using the same `launchOptions` ensures the browser configuration (window size, locale, humanization, proxy) is identical to the crawler, preventing fingerprint inconsistencies.\n- The function is standalone so it can be called from `main.ts` easily without modifying crawler internals.\n- Graceful error handling avoids aborting the crawl if Google is unreachable.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n- **File**: `src/warmup.ts`\n- **Imports**:\n  ```typescript\n  import { firefox } from 'playwright';\n  import log from 'apify/log';\n  ```\n- **Function signature** as above.\n- Use `await page.waitForTimeout()` (or `page.wait(ms)` – Playwright 1.60 uses `page.waitForTimeout`).\n- Google cookie dismiss: try `button:has-text('Accetta tutto')` then `button:has-text('Accept all')`.\n- Typing: use `page.keyboard.type()` with delay.\n- Mouse move: use `page.mouse.move()` with random coordinates.\n- **No extra dependencies**.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n\n- **Google not loading**: catch `TimeoutError` or other navigation errors, log warning, close browser, return normally. The crawl should proceed.\n- **Proxy errors**: if proxy fails, the warmup may fail; same handling – log warning, continue.\n- **Browser launch failure**: rare; log error and continue (crawler will launch its own browser later).\n- **Multiple warmups**: if called multiple times (not expected), each will launch a separate browser. OK.\n- **No proxyUrl provided**: use `launchOptions` as given (may already contain proxy from main.ts).\n\n## Validation\n\n- After implementation, verify the module can be imported without errors.\n- Run `npx tsx src/warmup.ts` (temporary test script) – should open and close Google successfully in headless mode.\n- Check that logs appear correctly with `[Warmup]` prefix.\n- Ensure no dangling browser processes remain after function returns (closed in `finally`).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n\n- **Inputs**: `launchOptions` object (from main.ts), optional `proxyUrl` string.\n- **Dependencies**: `playwright` (already installed), `apify/log` (already installed).\n- **No new npm packages**.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Must be ESM (type:module). Use `import` not `require`.\n- Follow project code style: single quotes, no `any` (use proper types from Playwright). For `launchOptions` use `import type { LaunchOptions } from 'playwright'`.\n- The function must **not** throw; any error must be caught and logged.\n- Keep code concise – no unnecessary abstractions.\n2. **Call warmup in main.ts before crawler.run**: ## Goal\nModify `src/main.ts` to import and call the `warmupBrowser` function (created in step `create-warmup-module`) **before** `crawler.run(startUrls)`. This ensures a mandatory Google warmup page with human-like interactions is executed on every Actor run, regardless of the input URLs.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification – insert import, call site, and error handling in the existing entry point file `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- `src/main.ts` (the only file to modify):\n  - Lines 148-160: PlaywrightCrawler instantiation with `camoufox-js` launch options, proxyConfiguration, hooks, router.\n  - Line 163 (approx): `await crawler.run(startUrls)` – the actual crawl start.\n  - Proxy is created from input (line 49-55): `Actor.createProxyConfiguration({ groups: ['RESIDENTIAL'], countryCode: 'IT' })` stored as `proxyConfiguration`.\n  - Import pattern: `import { /* symbols */ } from '@crawlee/playwright'` and `import { launchOptions } from './launch_options.js'` (or inline object).\n- `src/warmup.ts` (already created by previous step): exports `async function warmupBrowser(browserLaunchOptions: object, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>`.\n- The warmup module expects the same `launchOptions` object used for the crawler (camoufox-js config) and an optional proxy URL string (obtained from `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()`).\n\n## Action\n1. **Add import** at the top of `src/main.ts`:\n   ```typescript\n   import { warmupBrowser } from './warmup.js';\n   ```\n2. **Locate the insertion point**: immediately after the crawler is fully configured (after all hooks, before `await crawler.run(startUrls)`). In the current file, this is between the last `crawlerConfig` line and `await crawler.run(...)`.\n3. **Obtain a proxy URL** for the warmup page:\n   - The `proxyConfiguration` object is already available in scope.\n   - Use `const proxyUrl = await proxyConfiguration.newUrl();` to get a fresh proxy URL (same residential pool).\n4. **Insert the warmup call** with error handling:\n   ```typescript\n   // --- WARMUP PHASE: Google warmup for fingerprint priming ---\n   log.info('Starting mandatory warmup phase (Google interactions)');\n   try {\n       const warmupProxyUrl = await proxyConfiguration.newUrl();\n       await warmupBrowser(launchOptions, warmupProxyUrl);\n       log.info('Warmup completed successfully');\n   } catch (warmupError) {\n       log.warning('Warmup failed but continuing with target crawl', { error: warmupError.message });\n       // Warmup failure should not block crawling\n   }\n   ```\n   - Use `log` from `apify/log` (already imported).\n5. **Ensure no duplicate proxy call**: If `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()` is already called elsewhere (e.g., inside crawler config), it’s fine; each call returns a different sub-resident URL.\n6. **Preserve the existing `crawler.run` call** unchanged.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Placing warmup **after** crawler creation ensures browser launch options are final and consistent between warmup and actual crawling.\n- Using the same `proxyConfiguration` ensures the warmup page appears from the same IP class (Italian residential) as the subsequent crawl, avoiding sudden IP changes that could raise suspicion.\n- The try-catch prevents a warmup failure (e.g., network error, Google block) from aborting the entire Actor run; the target crawl will still proceed.\n- The call uses `await`, so the Actor pauses until warmup finishes (or fails), maintaining linear orchestration.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- **File**: `src/main.ts`\n- **Insert at**: line 162 (after crawler config block, before the `await crawler.run(startUrls)` line). Exact line number may vary; insert logically between the two blocks.\n- **No other files need changes**: `src/routes.ts`, `.actor/input_schema.json`, `Dockerfile`, `package.json` remain untouched.\n- **Imports to add**: `import { warmupBrowser } from './warmup.js';`\n- **Variables used**: `proxyConfiguration` (already in scope), `launchOptions` (already in scope), `log` (via `apify/log`).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()` throws (e.g., proxy pool exhausted), catch it and fall back to no proxy (undefined) – optional but safe.\n- If `warmupBrowser` throws (network timeout, Google captcha, etc.), log a warning and continue – the main crawl is not affected.\n- If the Actor is aborting during warmup (`Actor.on('aborting')`), the warmup function should check the abort signal and clean up promptly (handled internally by warmup module).\n- The warmup page is closed inside `warmupBrowser`, so no resource leak.\n\n## Validation\n1. Run `npm test` (Vitest) – existing integration test in `test/main.test.ts` must pass unchanged.\n2. Run the Actor locally with `tsx src/main.ts --input='{\"startUrls\":[{\"url\":\"https://apify.com\"}],\"maxRequestsPerCrawl\":5}'` – verify in logs that \"Starting mandatory warmup phase\" appears, followed by warmup completion (or warning).\n3. Check that the warmup page actually reached Google (e.g., add a temporary `page.screenshot` for debugging, then remove).\n4. Ensure no new TypeScript/ESLint errors (`npm run lint`).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- **Requires**: `src/warmup.ts` already created (step `create-warmup-module`) with exported `warmupBrowser`.\n- **Uses**: `proxyConfiguration` from `Actor.createProxyConfiguration(...)` in `main.ts`.\n- **No new npm packages** – all dependencies already installed.\n\n## Constraints\n- The warmup must be **unconditional** – always runs, no opt-out.\n- The warmup must reuse the **exact same Camoufox launch options** as the main crawler (stealth settings, window size, locale, etc.).\n- The warmup must **not** modify any global state (session pool, request queue) that would corrupt the subsequent crawl.\n- The warmup must complete within a reasonable time (default 30-second timeout recommended inside `warmupBrowser`).\n3. **Add warmup test cases in test/main.test.ts**: ## Goal\nAdd automated tests for the new warmup module (`src/warmup.ts`) to the existing test suite (`test/main.test.ts`). These tests must verify that:\n- The warmup function (`warmupBrowser`) can be called and completes without throwing.\n- The warmup function is correctly invoked before `crawler.run()` in `src/main.ts` (integration test).\n- The warmup does not break the existing crawl functionality.\n\n## Task Type\n**Test implementation** – Expand the Vitest test file to cover the warmup feature.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- **Test file**: `test/main.test.ts` – currently runs an integration test that creates a `PlaywrightCrawler`, requests 10 URLs from `https://apify.com`, and asserts `requestsFinished >= 10` and each dataset item has `url` and `title`.\n- **Warmup module**: `src/warmup.ts` (to be created by previous step `create-warmup-module`). It exports an async function `warmupBrowser(proxyConfiguration?: ProxyConfiguration): Promise<void>` that launches a Camoufox browser, navigates to Google, performs human-like interactions (typing, mouse moves, cookie dismissal), then closes the page and browser.\n- **Integration point**: In `src/main.ts`, after creating the `PlaywrightCrawler` and before `await crawler.run(startUrls)`, a call `await warmupBrowser(proxyConfiguration)` is inserted.\n- **Existing test structure**: uses `describe`, `it`, `expect`. Vitest with Playwright installed. The test file imports `Actor`, `ProxyConfiguration`, and uses `Actor.init()`/`Actor.exit()`.\n- **Browser launch**: Existing test relies on the crawler to launch Camoufox; the warmup test will need to call `warmupBrowser` directly, which also launches a Camoufox browser. Ensure the test can handle this (Camoufox binary must be available; Docker/CI has it).\n\n## Action\nModify `test/main.test.ts` to include the following test cases inside the existing `describe` block (or a new `describe` block):\n\n1. **Unit test for warmup function** (optional but recommended):\n   - Create a test that imports `warmupBrowser` from `../src/warmup.js` (ESM .js extension).\n   - Call `warmupBrowser()` with the same `proxyConfiguration` used in the existing test.\n   - Assert that the function resolves without throwing (use `await expect(warmupBrowser(proxyConfiguration)).resolves.toBeUndefined()`).\n   - Set a timeout of 60 seconds (browser launch + interactions may take time).\n\n2. **Integration test verifying warmup runs before crawl**:\n   - This test should call the main entry logic up to the point where warmup is invoked, but avoid actually crawling (or use a small crawl). Simpler approach: modify the existing integration test to **assert that the warmup function was called** (e.g., by spying on the warmup module or checking side effects). However, since the warmup is mandatory and runs inside `main.ts`, the best approach is to **trust that the existing crawl test still passes** after the warmup call is added. Therefore, add a test that imports `main` or runs the full actor (can be heavy).\n   - Alternatively, add a test that calls `main.ts` via `Actor.main()` (but that's complex). Instead, we can **add a separate integration test** that mimics the flow: create a proxy config, call warmup, then run the existing crawler test. This ensures the warmup does not break crawling.\n   - **Recommended approach**: Keep the existing test as is (it implicitly tests the whole flow including warmup). Then add a new test that directly calls `warmupBrowser` and afterward runs the same crawler logic but with minimal requests (e.g., 1 request). This validates the warmup + crawl pipeline.\n\n3. **Edge case test** (if time permits): Test warmup with invalid proxy (should fail gracefully via the error handling in `warmupBrowser`).\n\n## Reasoning\nThe warmup feature runs before every crawl; therefore, any regression in the warmup step could break all crawls. Adding specific tests for the warmup function ensures:\n- The function itself is independently testable.\n- The integration with the main flow remains stable.\n- Future changes to warmup behavior are covered.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n**File to modify**: `test/main.test.ts` (ESM, Vitest)\n\n**Test code template** (add inside the existing `describe('My Actor', () => { ... })` block or after it):\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect, beforeAll, afterAll } from 'vitest';\nimport { Actor } from 'apify';\nimport { warmupBrowser } from '../src/warmup.js';  // adjust path if necessary\n\ndescribe('Warmup integration', () => {\n    let proxyConfiguration;\n\n    beforeAll(async () => {\n        await Actor.init();\n        proxyConfiguration = await Actor.createProxyConfiguration({\n            groups: ['RESIDENTIAL'],\n            countryCode: 'IT',\n        });\n    }, 30000);\n\n    afterAll(async () => {\n        await Actor.exit();\n    });\n\n    it('warmupBrowser should execute without error', async () => {\n        await expect(warmupBrowser(proxyConfiguration)).resolves.toBeUndefined();\n    }, 120000);\n\n    it('warmup then crawl should work together', async () => {\n        // Run warmup\n        await warmupBrowser(proxyConfiguration);\n\n        // Run the existing crawl logic (reuse from existing test but with 1 request)\n        const crawler = ... // replicate minimal crawler creation from existing test, but with maxRequestsPerCrawl=1\n        // ... then assert at least one request finished and item has url+title\n        // This test validates that the warmup doesn't corrupt the browser/pool\n    }, 120000);\n});\n```\n\n- Use the same `ProxyConfiguration` instance that the existing test uses (create it once and share).\n- Set adequate timeouts (120 seconds for both tests) because browser launch, Google loading, and interactions can be slow.\n- Ensure the `warmupBrowser` function is imported with `.js` extension (ESM requirement).\n- The warmup function accepts `proxyConfiguration` as an optional parameter; pass it to reuse the same proxy.\n- The integration test should not exceed the existing test's resource usage; consider using `maxRequestsPerCrawl: 2` to keep it fast.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If the warmup function throws (e.g., Google blocks, network error), the test should fail clearly.\n- The warmup function should handle timeouts internally; test with a long timeout.\n- If the warmup module is not yet created (step dependency), the test import will fail – the step `create-warmup-module` must be completed first.\n- Do not mock the browser; tests must run with a real Camoufox instance (same as production). This ensures the real fingerprint warming works.\n- **Important**: The warmup function leaves the browser page and browser closed after completion. The subsequent crawl will open a new browser via the crawler – this is fine because Camoufox fingerprinting is per-launch? Actually, Camoufox generates a unique fingerprint per browser launch. The purpose is to warm up the fingerprint *before* the target crawl to make it look more natural. That means the warmup browser must be **reused** by the crawler, or the crawler should use the same browser instance. The current plan (steps `create-warmup-module` and `integrate-warmup-into-main`) likely expects the warmup to launch a separate browser and then close it, and the crawler later launches its own browser – which would not share the same fingerprint. However, the user’s intent is to warm the fingerprint for the same session. The integration test should reflect whatever design is implemented. If the warmup module reuses the crawler’s browser (via `newBrowserPage` on the existing `launchContext`), then the test must be adjusted. Based on the analysis, the warmup is a separate browser launch; thus the integration test should ensure it works regardless.\n\n## Validation\n- Run the test file with `npx vitest run test/main.test.ts` (or the full test suite) and confirm all tests pass.\n- Verify the warmup test completes within timeout and does not leave hanging browser processes (check for stray chrome/chromium processes). If hanging occurs, add proper cleanup in `afterAll`.\n- The existing test (which now implicitly includes the warmup call in `main.ts`) should still pass.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- Previous step `create-warmup-module` must have created `src/warmup.ts` with the correct export.\n- Previous step `integrate-warmup-into-main` must have added the warmup call in `src/main.ts`.\n- The existing test infrastructure (Vitest, Playwright, Camoufox binary) is already set up.\n- The test file uses `import { Actor } from 'apify'` – ensure `apify` is accessible.\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not add new dependencies (Vitest is already present).\n- Follow existing code conventions (ESM imports with `.js`, single quotes, 4-space indentation, etc.).\n- Do not modify `src/warmup.ts` or `src/main.ts` as part of this step; only modify the test file.\n- The warmup test should be independent of internet speed; set timeouts generously.\n- The test must be deterministic: if warmup fails due to external factors (Google changes), the test should be updated accordingly.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n- None – tests are internal.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n- Warmup tests add about 2 minutes to the test suite (two browser launches). This is acceptable for CI.\n- If tests become slow, consider splitting into separate test files due to parallelism limits.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n- None – tests do not produce documentation.\n\n## Diagram\nNot needed.\n4. **Execute full test suite to verify integration**: Step details are being generated.",
