      "content": "# CURRENT STEP SCOPE\n\n**Step 2 of 4**: Call warmup in main.ts before crawler.run\n\n## Goal\n## Goal\nModify `src/main.ts` to import and call the `warmupBrowser` function (created in step `create-warmup-module`) **before** `crawler.run(startUrls)`. This ensures a mandatory Google warmup page with human-like interactions is executed on every Actor run, regardless of the input URLs.\n\n## Task Type\nCode modification – insert import, call site, and error handling in the existing entry point file `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- `src/main.ts` (the only file to modify):\n  - Lines 148-160: PlaywrightCrawler instantiation with `camoufox-js` launch options, proxyConfiguration, hooks, router.\n  - Line 163 (approx): `await crawler.run(startUrls)` – the actual crawl start.\n  - Proxy is created from input (line 49-55): `Actor.createProxyConfiguration({ groups: ['RESIDENTIAL'], countryCode: 'IT' })` stored as `proxyConfiguration`.\n  - Import pattern: `import { /* symbols */ } from '@crawlee/playwright'` and `import { launchOptions } from './launch_options.js'` (or inline object).\n- `src/warmup.ts` (already created by previous step): exports `async function warmupBrowser(browserLaunchOptions: object, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>`.\n- The warmup module expects the same `launchOptions` object used for the crawler (camoufox-js config) and an optional proxy URL string (obtained from `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()`).\n\n## Action\n1. **Add import** at the top of `src/main.ts`:\n   ```typescript\n   import { warmupBrowser } from './warmup.js';\n   ```\n2. **Locate the insertion point**: immediately after the crawler is fully configured (after all hooks, before `await crawler.run(startUrls)`). In the current file, this is between the last `crawlerConfig` line and `await crawler.run(...)`.\n3. **Obtain a proxy URL** for the warmup page:\n   - The `proxyConfiguration` object is already available in scope.\n   - Use `const proxyUrl = await proxyConfiguration.newUrl();` to get a fresh proxy URL (same residential pool).\n4. **Insert the warmup call** with error handling:\n   ```typescript\n   // --- WARMUP PHASE: Google warmup for fingerprint priming ---\n   log.info('Starting mandatory warmup phase (Google interactions)');\n   try {\n       const warmupProxyUrl = await proxyConfiguration.newUrl();\n       await warmupBrowser(launchOptions, warmupProxyUrl);\n       log.info('Warmup completed successfully');\n   } catch (warmupError) {\n       log.warning('Warmup failed but continuing with target crawl', { error: warmupError.message });\n       // Warmup failure should not block crawling\n   }\n   ```\n   - Use `log` from `apify/log` (already imported).\n5. **Ensure no duplicate proxy call**: If `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()` is already called elsewhere (e.g., inside crawler config), it’s fine; each call returns a different sub-resident URL.\n6. **Preserve the existing `crawler.run` call** unchanged.\n\n## Reasoning\n- Placing warmup **after** crawler creation ensures browser launch options are final and consistent between warmup and actual crawling.\n- Using the same `proxyConfiguration` ensures the warmup page appears from the same IP class (Italian residential) as the subsequent crawl, avoiding sudden IP changes that could raise suspicion.\n- The try-catch prevents a warmup failure (e.g., network error, Google block) from aborting the entire Actor run; the target crawl will still proceed.\n- The call uses `await`, so the Actor pauses until warmup finishes (or fails), maintaining linear orchestration.\n\n## Implementation Details\n- **File**: `src/main.ts`\n- **Insert at**: line 162 (after crawler config block, before the `await crawler.run(startUrls)` line). Exact line number may vary; insert logically between the two blocks.\n- **No other files need changes**: `src/routes.ts`, `.actor/input_schema.json`, `Dockerfile`, `package.json` remain untouched.\n- **Imports to add**: `import { warmupBrowser } from './warmup.js';`\n- **Variables used**: `proxyConfiguration` (already in scope), `launchOptions` (already in scope), `log` (via `apify/log`).\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `proxyConfiguration.newUrl()` throws (e.g., proxy pool exhausted), catch it and fall back to no proxy (undefined) – optional but safe.\n- If `warmupBrowser` throws (network timeout, Google captcha, etc.), log a warning and continue – the main crawl is not affected.\n- If the Actor is aborting during warmup (`Actor.on('aborting')`), the warmup function should check the abort signal and clean up promptly (handled internally by warmup module).\n- The warmup page is closed inside `warmupBrowser`, so no resource leak.\n\n## Validation\n1. Run `npm test` (Vitest) – existing integration test in `test/main.test.ts` must pass unchanged.\n2. Run the Actor locally with `tsx src/main.ts --input='{\"startUrls\":[{\"url\":\"https://apify.com\"}],\"maxRequestsPerCrawl\":5}'` – verify in logs that \"Starting mandatory warmup phase\" appears, followed by warmup completion (or warning).\n3. Check that the warmup page actually reached Google (e.g., add a temporary `page.screenshot` for debugging, then remove).\n4. Ensure no new TypeScript/ESLint errors (`npm run lint`).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- **Requires**: `src/warmup.ts` already created (step `create-warmup-module`) with exported `warmupBrowser`.\n- **Uses**: `proxyConfiguration` from `Actor.createProxyConfiguration(...)` in `main.ts`.\n- **No new npm packages** – all dependencies already installed.\n\n## Constraints\n- The warmup must be **unconditional** – always runs, no opt-out.\n- The warmup must reuse the **exact same Camoufox launch options** as the main crawler (stealth settings, window size, locale, etc.).\n- The warmup must **not** modify any global state (session pool, request queue) that would corrupt the subsequent crawl.\n- The warmup must complete within a reasonable time (default 30-second timeout recommended inside `warmupBrowser`).\n\nThis is the ONLY task you must complete in this iteration. Do not work on other steps.",
